    <div class="quiz-section">
        <h2>Essay Questions (5 questions)</h2>
        
        <div class="question" id="eq1">
            <p>1. Explain the difference between the intended applications of Grades 42, 50, and 55 versus Grades 60 and 65 according to ASTM A572/A572M-21.</p>
            <textarea id="answer-eq1" placeholder="Type your answer here..."></textarea>
            <button onclick="showEssayAnswer('eq1', 'Grades 42, 50, and 55 are intended for riveted, bolted, or welded structures, while Grades 60 and 65 are intended primarily for riveted or bolted construction of bridges, though they can also be used for riveted, bolted, or welded construction in other applications. The standard notes that for welded bridge construction where notch toughness is important, requirements should be negotiated between purchaser and producer.')">Show Answer</button>
            <div class="essay-answer" id="essay-answer-eq1"></div>
        </div>

        <div class="question" id="eq2">
            <p>2. Describe the chemical composition requirements for ASTM A572 Grade 50 steel, including any permitted variations based on product thickness.</p>
            <textarea id="answer-eq2" placeholder="Type your answer here..."></textarea>
            <button onclick="showEssayAnswer('eq2', 'For Grade 50 [345], the maximum carbon content is 0.23% by heat analysis. The maximum manganese content is 1.35%, with a minimum of 0.80% required for plates over 3/8 in. [10 mm] thick, and 0.50% minimum for thinner plates and other products. The manganese to carbon ratio must not be less than 2:1. Maximum phosphorus and sulfur are 0.030% each. Silicon content must be between 0.15-0.40%. For each 0.01% reduction below the carbon maximum, manganese can be increased by 0.06% up to 1.60% maximum.')">Show Answer</button>
            <div class="essay-answer" id="essay-answer-eq2"></div>
        </div>

        <div class="question" id="eq3">
            <p>3. What are the four types of alloy content specified in ASTM A572, and what elements are included in each type?</p>
            <textarea id="answer-eq3" placeholder="Type your answer here..."></textarea>
            <button onclick="showEssayAnswer('eq3', 'The four types are: 1) Type 1: Columbium/niobium (0.005-0.05%), 2) Type 2: Vanadium (0.01-0.15%), 3) Type 3: Columbium/niobium (0.005-0.05%) plus vanadium (0.01-0.15%), with combined content of 0.02-0.15%, and 4) Type 5: Titanium (0.006-0.04%), nitrogen (0.003-0.015%), and vanadium (0.06% max). The producer can select the type unless otherwise specified by the purchaser.')">Show Answer</button>
            <div class="essay-answer" id="essay-answer-eq3"></div>
        </div>

        <div class="question" id="eq4">
            <p>4. Discuss the mechanical property requirements for ASTM A572 Grade 60 steel, including yield point, tensile strength, and elongation.</p>
            <textarea id="answer-eq4" placeholder="Type your answer here..."></textarea>
            <button onclick="showEssayAnswer('eq4', 'For Grade 60 [415], the minimum yield point is 60 ksi [415 MPa]. The minimum tensile strength is 75 ksi [520 MPa]. Elongation requirements are 16% minimum in 8 in. (200 mm) and 18% minimum in 2 in. (50 mm). For plates wider than 24 in. (600 mm), the elongation requirement is reduced by three percentage points. For wide flange shapes over 426 lb/ft [634 kg/m], elongation in 2 in. (50 mm) of 19% minimum applies.')">Show Answer</button>
            <div class="essay-answer" id="essay-answer-eq4"></div>
        </div>

        <div class="question" id="eq5">
            <p>5. Explain the key changes made in the 2021 revision of ASTM A572 compared to the 2018 version.</p>
            <textarea id="answer-eq5" placeholder="Type your answer here..."></textarea>
            <button onclick="showEssayAnswer('eq5', 'Key changes in the 2021 revision include: 1) Adding niobium as an interchangeable name for columbium throughout the standard, 2) Increasing maximum thickness for Grade 55 plates/bars from 2 in. to 2½ in., 3) Increasing maximum thickness for Grade 60 plates/bars from 1¼ in. to 2½ in., 4) Increasing maximum thickness for Grade 65 plates/bars from 1¼ in. to 2 in., and 5) Corresponding updates to Table 2 to reflect these thickness changes.')">Show Answer</button>
            <div class="essay-answer" id="essay-answer-eq5"></div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <script>
        function checkAnswer(questionId, correctAnswer, feedbackText) {
            const selectedOption = document.querySelector(`input[name="${questionId}"]:checked`);
            const feedbackElement = document.getElementById(`feedback-${questionId}`);
            
            if (!selectedOption) {
                alert("Please select an answer!");
                return;
            }
            
            if (selectedOption.value === correctAnswer) {
                feedbackElement.textContent = feedbackText;
                feedbackElement.className = "feedback correct";
            } else {
                feedbackElement.textContent = "Incorrect. " + feedbackText;
                feedbackElement.className = "feedback incorrect";
            }
            
            feedbackElement.style.display = "block";
        }

        function showEssayAnswer(questionId, correctAnswer) {
            const answerElement = document.getElementById(`essay-answer-${questionId}`);
            answerElement.textContent = correctAnswer;
            answerElement.style.display = "block";
        }
    </script>
